title: For Sale:  Mini 1911 in 32 ACP
postcontent: "Llama Especial" in 32 ACP.  (Don't think of the goofy animal--"Llama" means "Flame" in Spanish and that's the company name.)  Also known as the Llama IIIA, the "Flame Special" is a miniature 1911: controls and disassembles just like the real thing.  Produced in Spain in the 1970s, it has all original parts, springs, and bluing, with some wear.  Sights are drift-adjustible in the rear and there is a flat-finished vent-rib along the top of the slide.  Magazine capacity is 9 rounds.This is a great gun for a newer shooter to learn on, particularly if you've got a youngster who wants to move up from 22LR but isn't quite ready yet for the real deal.  The straight-blowback operation makes the slide easy to rack, particularly for younger/weaker hands, and the 32 ACP recoil is milder than full-caliber guns or even 380 ACP.  I used this gun to teach my daughter to shoot 1911s.  She's moved on to other things now, and I'm putting this up for sale.  Comes with 2 mags.I will sell locally in Kitsap County or the Tacoma/JBLM area.  Cash or USPS Money Orders are the only forms of payment accepted.  Gun is sold as-is, with no warranty, and the sale is final.  Buyer is responsible for all fees associated with transfer, we can meet at the FFL of your choice to handle the transfer IAW WA law.

title: For Sale:  1864 SPRINGFIELD Allin Conversion Model TRAPDOOR
postcontent: As the US Civil War drew to a close, it was quite apparent to everyone that muzzleloading rifles were obsolete, and any military force wishing to remain relevant would need to adopt cartridge-firing weapons. However, the Union arsenals had a million or more muzzleloading rifled muskets still on hand. How to modernize the weaponry without simply throwing away all those existing guns? The task was put to Springfield Arsenal master armorer Erskine Allin in 1864, and he devised a “trapdoor” style of conversion to turn an old Springfield muzzleloader into a breechloader. He had the benefit of having seen the previous year’s extensive trials of breechloaders, but the final product was his combination of what he judged to be the best elements of the ideas available. The result has long been known colloquially as the Trapdoor Springfield, and this 1864 model was the very first of them. It was still in .58 caliber, and used a rather complex extractor system. It would soon be revised to make improvements to it, and ultimately a .45-70 model became standard for US infantry and cavalry forces – and remained their standard until the adoption of the Krag-Jorgensen in the 1890s. 3% Surcharge on all Credit Card TransactionsNO CALIFORNIA SALES!

title: For Sale:  Remington Model 1903-A3
postcontent: This is a very fine condition and all original, Remington Arms Model 1903-A3 from early in WWII. This particular rifle was manufactured during the period when Remington was transitioning from the Model 1903 Rifle to the Model 1903-A3 rifle. Transition rifles occur during an approximately 3 month period from December 1942 to February or early March 1943. There are no rebuild, arsenal marks or import stamps anywhere on this rifle. The stock on this 1903-A3 is the original and early Remington-manufactured “S” or straight stock for the 1903-A3 that is in excellent condition with the original finish. There are normal dings and handling marks on the stock and there is a small, 1 ½” hairline crack on the top to the rear of the receiver cutout that does not go all the way through and which remains solid. The left side of the stock has the correct Ordnance Escutcheon Stamp, followed by the correct boxed “FJA” cartouche of Colonel Frank J. Atwood, who was the U.S. Army Ordnance Inspector for the northeast United States during WWII, which encompassed Remington’s firearms plant at Ilion, New York. The sans serif “RA” Remington Arms stamp only appeared later on 1903-A3 stocks. The bottom of the wrist has the correct circle “P” firing proof without serifs as well as a serif “P” stamp just to the rear of the proof stamp. Just forward of the trigger guard recess are the Remington-typical sub-inspection stampings, which include two circles with numbers (“11” and “5”), a triangle with a “2” stamp and a square with “53.” In the trigger guard cutout is a serif “L” stamp. In the receiver and barrel cutouts are a “&” stamp, the number “55” and a serif “B” stamp. There is more of this description but whenever I find a serious buyer I will tell them more about the rifle...

title: For Sale:  1955 Mosin Nagant Chinese T53
postcontent: Chinese production of the carbine began in 1953 and the designation of this new carbine was the Type 53 . The early proofs on the barrel shank of the Type 53 will have both Chinese characters and the number 26 or 296. The Chinese characters translate to " 53 Year Type " and the 26 or 296 are the stamping of the State Factory at Chongqing. In many later production Type 53's the Chinese characters are not present but it is not known why the characters were dropped. The shank proofs also became larger in 1960 but again the reason for this action is not entirely clear. The Chinese did not use the large number of stamps on the carbine's metal as their Soviet allies; however, the Chinese more than made up for this with the large number of proofs that appear on most Type 53 stocks. It is not uncommon to have ten or more various stamps on these stocks. The wood used on most of these stocks is not the high quality as that used in the Soviet carbines; however, the wood on the Type 53 is quite solid and competent. The Chinese utilized a local wood that is known as CHU-wood. The CHU-wood was put to use as it was quite effective in standing up to so called "Jungle Rot." The wood was quite proficient in resisting moisture, so was a perfect choice for the environment of Asia. There are some Type 53 stocks that have their serial numbers matched to the carbines, with these numbers appearing on the left side on the stock.

title: For Sale:  1955 Chinese Mosin Nagant T53
postcontent: Chinese production of the carbine began in 1953 and the designation of this new carbine was the Type 53 . The early proofs on the barrel shank of the Type 53 will have both Chinese characters and the number 26 or 296. The Chinese characters translate to " 53 Year Type " and the 26 or 296 are the stamping of the State Factory at Chongqing. In many later production Type 53's the Chinese characters are not present but it is not known why the characters were dropped. The shank proofs also became larger in 1960 but again the reason for this action is not entirely clear. The Chinese did not use the large number of stamps on the carbine's metal as their Soviet allies; however, the Chinese more than made up for this with the large number of proofs that appear on most Type 53 stocks. It is not uncommon to have ten or more various stamps on these stocks. The wood used on most of these stocks is not the high quality as that used in the Soviet carbines; however, the wood on the Type 53 is quite solid and competent. The Chinese utilized a local wood that is known as CHU-wood. The CHU-wood was put to use as it was quite effective in standing up to so called "Jungle Rot." The wood was quite proficient in resisting moisture, so was a perfect choice for the environment of Asia. There are some Type 53 stocks that have their serial numbers matched to the carbines, with these numbers appearing on the left side on the stock.
